dsDescriptionValue.value:
This widely used personality assessment instrument was developed in 1941 by Hathaway and McKinley in response to an apparent need to assess the psychological factors associated with physical problems and diseases. It was believed that the MMPI would fill the need for 'an easily applicable measuring device which would identify and characterize the psychoneurotic patient with a minimum use of time-consuming interview technic...' (McKinley and Hathaway, 1943). Although originally developed for u se with a psychiatric population, the MMPI has been found to be of considerable value in assessing personality functioning over a much broader spectrum of educational, occupational, consultation, and counseling applications.

In CAPS/87, a new version of the MMPI was administered (Form AX). This form eliminates 16 duplicated items and adds 150 new items to bring the total to 704 T/F items.

Scoring information: The MMPI Form AX consists of 704 true-false items. The Dahlstrom reference cited below documents 455 subscales which may be constructed from the MMPI items.

For the user's convenience, 36 commonly used scales have been constructed and stored with individual item scores.

See codebook for additional information
